To make API calls from JavaScript to your weather service using your API key (ABC123XYZ), you can use the `fetch` API, which is built into modern browsers and easy to use.

Here’s a basic example of how you might do this to get temperature (in Fahrenheit) and humidity for a specific city:

```javascript
const apiKey = 'ABC123XYZ';
const city = 'New York'; // change to your desired city
const units = 'imperial'; // 'imperial' for Fahrenheit, 'metric' for Celsius

const url = `https://api.weatherprovider.com/data?city=${encodeURIComponent(city)}&units=${units}&apikey=${apiKey}`;

async function fetchWeather() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url);
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }
    const data = await response.json();
    // Assuming the API response structure, adjust based on actual API docs
    const temperature = data.main.temp;
    const humidity = data.main.humidity;
    const locationName = data.name;

    // Update the HTML elements
    document.getElementById('location').textContent = locationName;
    document.getElementById('temperature').textContent = `${temperature} °F`;
    document.getElementById('humidity').textContent = `${humidity} %`;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching weather data:', error);
    document.getElementById('location').textContent = 'Failed to load data';
  }
}

// Call the function to fetch weather on page load
fetchWeather();
```

### Notes:
- Replace `https://api.weatherprovider.com/data` with the actual endpoint URL of your weather service.
- The query parameters (`city`, `units`, `apikey`) may differ depending on your API provider’s specification. Check your API documentation for exact parameters.
- This example assumes the API returns a JSON object with a `main` field containing `temp` and `humidity`, and a `name` field for the location name—typical for many weather APIs like OpenWeatherMap.
- The `units` parameter is set to `'imperial'` for Fahrenheit as you selected earlier.
- Make sure your HTML includes elements with IDs `location`, `temperature`, and `humidity` as in your layout.

